<subSubSection pageId="17" pageNumber="329" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="17.[816,1430,1185,2019]" box="[816,955,1185,1211]" pageId="17" pageNumber="329">
<emphasis box="[816,955,1185,1211]" italics="true" pageId="17" pageNumber="329">Description</emphasis>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="17.[816,1430,1185,2019]" pageId="17" pageNumber="329">
With a forearm length of 
<quantity box="[1170,1344,1219,1245]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="4.709999999999999" metricValueMax="4.88" metricValueMin="4.54" pageId="17" pageNumber="329" unit="mm" value="47.099999999999994" valueMax="48.8" valueMin="45.4">45.4–48.8 mm</quantity>
(
<tableCitation captionStart="TABLE" captionStartId="7.[159,172,220,241]" captionTargetPageId="7" captionText="TABLE 2. External measurements (mm) and bacular length (mm) of 14 bat species recently collected at Lekoumou, Congo.Acronyms explained in the Materials and Methods section include means, ranges, and, where relevant, standard deviations. Numbers in parentheses refer to sample size where they differ from those stated in column 2" httpUri="http://table.plazi.org/id/5FAA6645FF93C07DFF03FF23FC6EFEEE" pageId="17" pageNumber="329" tableUuid="5FAA6645FF93C07DFF03FF23FC6EFEEE">Table 2</tableCitation>
), this species is typical of the genus in having the second phalanx of the third digit greatly elongated (37.0– 
<quantity box="[894,1013,1320,1346]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="3.88" pageId="17" pageNumber="329" unit="mm" value="38.8">38.8 mm</quantity>
, 
<emphasis box="[1036,1051,1320,1346]" italics="true" pageId="17" pageNumber="329">n</emphasis>
= 4). The interfemoral and wing membranes and the pelage, above and below, are dark. However, the face and especially the lower part of each inner ear and tragus are almost white. The tragus is tall, straight-sided, with a rounded tip, and a small indication of a basal lobe (
<figureCitation box="[826,922,1522,1548]" captionStart="FIG" captionStartId="11.[159,172,1911,1932]" captionTargetBox="[287,1299,1270,1885]" captionTargetId="figure@11.[211,1406,1263,1892]" captionTargetPageId="11" captionText="FIG. 8. Right tragus of (A): Glauconycteris alboguttata, HZM.1.40172, ♀; (B): G. beatrix, HZM.1.40181, ♀; (C): Hypsugo crassulus, HZM.1.40190, ♂; (D): Neoromicia brunnea, HZM.1.40191, ♂; (E): N. nana, HZM.321.40186, ♂; (F): N. tenuipinnis, HZM.7.40170, ♀; (G): Pipistrellus nanulus, HZM.1.40189, ♂; (H): Mimetillus moloneyi, HZM.10.40177, ♂; (I): Miniopterus inflatus, HZM.19.40182, ♂. Scale = 2 mm" figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3943579" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3943579/files/figure.png" pageId="17" pageNumber="329">Fig. 8I</figureCitation>
). The skull is characteristically large with a greatest length of 
<quantity box="[1108,1308,1555,1581]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.6789999999999998" metricValueMax="1.716" metricValueMin="1.642" pageId="17" pageNumber="329" unit="mm" value="16.79" valueMax="17.16" valueMin="16.42">16.42–17.16 mm</quantity>
(
<tableCitation box="[1323,1413,1555,1581]" captionStart="TABLE" captionStartId="8.[99,112,725,746]" captionTargetPageId="8" captionText="TABLE 3. Cranial and dental measurements (mm) of 14 bat species recently collected at Lekoumou, Congo.Acronyms explained in the Materials and Methods section include means, ranges, and, where relevant,standard deviations. Numbers in parentheses refer to sample size where they differ from those stated in column 2" httpUri="http://table.plazi.org/id/5FAA6645FF9CC072FFFFFD2AFAA7FCC7" pageId="17" pageNumber="329" tableUuid="5FAA6645FF9CC072FFFFFD2AFAA7FCC7">Table 3</tableCitation>
). The braincase is greatly inflated and is sharply elevated above the small, flattened rostrum. The first upper incisor (I 
<superScript attach="right" box="[1003,1013,1652,1670]" fontSize="8" pageId="17" pageNumber="329">2</superScript>
) has a broad, tricuspid crown; the second (I 
<superScript attach="right" box="[927,937,1685,1703]" fontSize="8" pageId="17" pageNumber="329">3</superScript>
) is unicuspid with a well developed cingulum. The first upper premolar (P 
<superScript attach="left" box="[1237,1247,1719,1737]" fontSize="8" pageId="17" pageNumber="329">2</superScript>
) is well developed and between half and two-thirds the crown area of the second premolar (P 
<superScript attach="left" box="[1184,1194,1786,1804]" fontSize="8" pageId="17" pageNumber="329">4</superScript>
). The first and second lower premolars (P 
<subScript attach="left" box="[1102,1112,1839,1857]" fontSize="8" pageId="17" pageNumber="329">2</subScript>
, P 
<subScript attach="left" box="[1146,1156,1839,1857]" fontSize="8" pageId="17" pageNumber="329">3</subScript>
) are equal in size and about half the crown area and height of the third (P 
<subScript attach="left" box="[843,853,1906,1924]" fontSize="8" pageId="17" pageNumber="329">4</subScript>
). Despite dissecting the penis, no baculum was found; this agrees with 
<bibRefCitation author="Krutzsch" box="[1168,1429,1925,1951]" firstAuthor="Krutzsch" pageId="17" pageNumber="329" refId="ref14158" refString="KRUTZSCH, P. H. 2000. Anatomy, physiology and cyclicity of the male reproductive tract. Pp. 91 - 156, in Reproductive biology of bats (E. G. CRICHTON and P. H. KRUTZSCH, eds.). Academic Press, London, 522 pp." type="book" year="2000">Krutzsch (2000: 105)</bibRefCitation>
who also reported the absence of a baculum in 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Bonaparte" authorityYear="1837" box="[816,959,1993,2019]" class="Mammalia" family="Miniopteridae" genus="Miniopterus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Chiroptera" pageId="17" pageNumber="329" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[816,959,1993,2019]" italics="true" pageId="17" pageNumber="329">Miniopterus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="18" pageNumber="330" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="18.[159,771,220,415]" box="[159,356,220,246]" pageId="18" pageNumber="330">
<emphasis box="[159,356,220,246]" italics="true" pageId="18" pageNumber="330">Taxonomic notes</emphasis>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="18.[159,771,220,415]" pageId="18" pageNumber="330">
The taxonomy of African 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Bonaparte" authorityYear="1837" box="[505,648,254,280]" class="Mammalia" family="Miniopteridae" genus="Miniopterus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Chiroptera" pageId="18" pageNumber="330" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[505,648,254,280]" italics="true" pageId="18" pageNumber="330">Miniopterus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is in need of revision, for example to determine the distinction between 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Thomas" authorityYear="1903" box="[266,394,321,347]" class="Mammalia" family="Miniopteridae" genus="Miniopterus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Chiroptera" pageId="18" pageNumber="330" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="inflatus">
<emphasis box="[266,394,321,347]" italics="true" pageId="18" pageNumber="330">M. inflatus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName authority="(Simmons, 2005)" baseAuthorityName="Simmons" baseAuthorityYear="2005" class="Mammalia" family="Miniopteridae" genus="Miniopterus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Chiroptera" pageId="18" pageNumber="330" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="schreibersii">
<emphasis box="[458,634,321,347]" italics="true" pageId="18" pageNumber="330">M. schreibersii</emphasis>
(
<bibRefCitation author="Simmons" firstAuthor="Simmons" pageId="18" pageNumber="330" refId="ref14567" refString="SIMMONS, N. B. 2005. Order Chiroptera. Pp. 312 - 529, in Mammals species of the World (D. E. WILSON and D. M. REEDER, eds). Johns Hopkins University Press, Baltimore, 2142 pp." type="book" year="2005">Simmons, 2005</bibRefCitation>
)
</taxonomicName>
. Following 
<bibRefCitation author="Happold and Happold" box="[371,721,355,381]" firstAuthor="Happold" pageId="18" pageNumber="330" refId="ref13898" refString="HAPPOLD, M., and D. C. D. HAPPOLD (eds.). 2013. Mammals of Africa Volume IV: Hedgehogs, shrews, and bats. Bloomsbury Publishing, London, 800 pp." type="book" year="2013">Happold and Happold (2013)</bibRefCitation>
, the new records from 
<collectingCountry box="[367,444,389,415]" name="Democratic Republic of the Congo" pageId="18" pageNumber="330">Congo</collectingCountry>
are referred to 
<emphasis box="[618,771,389,415]" italics="true" pageId="18" pageNumber="330">
M. i. 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Thomas" authorityYear="1903" box="[678,767,389,415]" class="Mammalia" family="Miniopteridae" genus="Miniopterus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Chiroptera" pageId="18" pageNumber="330" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="inflatus">inflatus</taxonomicName>
.
</emphasis>
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
